Tanzania Modeling Document¶

Prepared by Reduce.Reuse.Grow.Inc¶

Abstract¶

RRG has partnered with the Friends of the Usambara (FOU) to conduct Project Forest throughout the Usambara mountains of northeastern Tanzania. RRG and FOU have partnered to plant 6.49 million trees over ~4200 hectares and is planning the expansion of 10 million trees or ~ 6200 hectares. RRG and FOU have conducted forest inventories of diameter at breast height (DBH) and age. Using geospatial data (LiDAR), RRG has trained parametric regression models of forest inventory data to forecast biomass changes per hectare over the project lifetime (50 years). RRG has created a range of quartile based performance scenarios for forecasting biomass changes. In total, RRG estimates that Project Forest can potentially sequester 1,030,776 - 4,123,103 tCo2e throughout the project lifetime.
To monitor and quantify biomass change, RRG utilizes Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) and LiDAR biomass maps provided by Google Earth Engine (GEE). RRG is able to access a broad range of temporal data and is able to establish the baseline biomass within the project area. As the stand develops, RRG will track biomass changes to train and validate forecasts.

System Overview¶

RRG's modeling system is designed to estimate carbon removals and project emissions for Project ReGAIN. RRG will leverage field data, remote sensing, and statistical learning tools within Python, Google Earth Engine (GEE) and ArcGIS Pro. The workflow is structured arround Verra's VM0047 Methodology, which provides transparent, data-driven methodologies to track biomass change and net climate benefits over time.

System Goals¶

The primary goals of the system are to:

  1. Quantify forest biomass and changes using field inventories and remote sensing data.
  2. Estimate carbon removals and project emissions (e.g., from planting, fertilizer use and leakage).
  3. Calculate net carbon benefits and project future VCUs.
  4. Evaluate the performance of machine learning models.

Data Specifications¶

Collection Period¶

A 2021 study by Gaworek, et al. analyzed the eastern Usambara mountains precipitation levels from 1969-2019. Below is the monthly precipitation graph created by the study.

The Usambara's have two distinct rainy seasons, from March to May and from September to November. RRG will select imagery for study from the dry season, specifically from December-February in an effort to

  • Reduce seasonal phenological variation
  • Select months with the lowest cloud cover

SAR and LiDAR imagery are less suceptible to the above changes, however RRG will consistently select imagery from July for analysis. For training models, RRG uses a median value of all available data for the year.

Coordinate Systems¶

RRG will utilize two coordinate systems. One geographic coordinate system for web based applications, the other projected coordinate system for area analysis when area quantification must be as accurate as possible:

  • Geographic Coordinate System: WGS 1984, EPSG: 4326
  • Projected Coordinate System: WGS 1984 UTM Zone 37S, EPSG:32737

Technology Stack¶

RRG will utilize industry standard technologies for data science, remote sensing and forest monitoring. The following technology stack will be used in development and implementation of RRG's modeling system.

Remote Sensing

  • ArcGIS Pro
  • Google Earth Engine (GEE)

Data Science

  • Python

Reporting

  • RRG's dMRV site
  • Jupyter lab Methodology Notebooks

Biomass Training Dataset Collection¶

RRG aims to train field inventory models based on validated LiDAR biomass training datasets provided by NASA and the UN. RRG aims to evaluate each dataset to select the most accurate representation of the Mindano region. RRG will utilize the training datasets to add biological caps to inventory models. Furthermore, RRG will train Stocking Index (SI) values on LiDAR biomass datasets to track changes in forest structure.

def quality_mask(im):
    return im.updateMask(im.select('l4_quality_flag').eq(1)) \
             .updateMask(im.select('degrade_flag').eq(0)) \
             .updateMask(im.select('agbd').gt(0))  
year = 2020

    .filterBounds(projectsites)\
    .filterDate(f'{year}-01-01', f'{year + 1}-04-01')

Selected Biomass Source
GEDI data is sparse within the Usambara mountains. Therefore, RRG will use the dataset's provided by the UN and NASA for field inventory training. Between these sources, old growth forests throughout the region range from 120 - 140 tC/ha. For inventory model training, RRG has selected a biological cap ~ 140 tC/ha. For SI model training, RRG utilizies all three biomass datasets.

Field Inventories¶

RRG and FOU conducted initial field inventories of species to be planted. Because GEE datasets do not provide forest age data, RRG can use inventory data to forecast carbon removals throughout the project lifetime.
RRG will first convert DBH to mass (t) by utilizing allometric equations. RRG then models age and biomass data to predict potential biomass of the site throughout the project lifetime. The following equation describes the model: $$ \text{Biomass (kg/tree)} = f(\text{Age}) $$

Allometric Conversion
To convert DBH into aboveground weight (kg), RRG has conducted a thorough analysis of allometric equations for the Usambara region. RRG chose the most conservative allometric equation created for the Usambara region provided by R.E. Malimbwi.

def allo(x):
    eq = (( 0.9635 * x ** 1.9440 ) * .001)

def ql(data):
    df = data.iloc[:, [0,1]]
    x = df.iloc[:,0]
    y = df.iloc[:,1]
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]
    #Statistics
    df.corr()
    spearman_corr = x.corr(y, method='spearman')
    print('Spearman Correlation:', spearman_corr)
    # Calculate standard deviations
    std_x = df[xName].std()
    std_y = df[yName].std()
    # Create text for standard deviation
    textstrx = f'Standard Deviation of\n{xName}: {std_x:.2f}'
    textstry = f'Standard Deviation of\n{yName}: {std_y:.2f}'
    props = dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor='grey', alpha=0.5)
    # statistical graphs
    sns.set_theme()
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(10, 8))  
    axs = axs.flatten() 
    #Scatter plot distribution
    sns.scatterplot(x = f"{xName}", y = f"{yName}", data = df, alpha=0.5, color='purple', ax=axs[0])
    axs[0].set_title('Scatter Plot')
    axs[0].set_xlabel(f'{xName}')
    axs[0].set_ylabel(f'{yName}')
    #heatmap of correlations
    sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', ax=axs[1], cbar=True, cbar_kws={"label": "Correlation Coefficient"})
    axs[1].set_title('Correlation Heatmap')
    # hist plot
    sns.histplot(df[f"{xName}"], kde=True, color="darkgreen", ax=axs[2])
    axs[2].set_title(f'Distribution of {xName}')
    axs[2].set_xlabel(f'{xName}')
    axs[2].text(0.98, 0.95, textstrx, transform=axs[2].transAxes, fontsize=8,
        verticalalignment='top', bbox=props, horizontalalignment='right')
    sns.histplot(df[f"{yName}"], kde=True, color="darkgreen", ax=axs[3])
    axs[3].set_title(f'Distribution of {yName}')
    axs[3].text(0.98, 0.95, textstry, transform=axs[3].transAxes, fontsize=8,
        verticalalignment='top', bbox=props, horizontalalignment='right')
    axs[3].set_xlabel(f'{yName}')
    fig.suptitle(f'Distribution of {xName} and {yName}')
    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.92], pad=1.0)
    plt.show()

Model Design¶

RRG has created a parametric regression modeling function to be used for carbon forecasts. The function utilizes 2nd Polynomial, 3rd Polynomial, Logarithmic, Power and Chapman-Richard's equations to predict biomass given age. Included in the function are statistical metrics including R2, RMSE and MPE to track model quality.

In [69]:
def model(data):
    df = data.copy()
    x = df.iloc[:, 0]
    y = df.iloc[:, 1]
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]
    # PARAMETRIC MODELING
    #linear modeling/polynomial 
    results = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName}', data=df, weights=df['weights']).fit()
    poly2 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2)', data=df, weights=df['weights']).fit()
    poly3 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2) + I({xName}**3)', data=df, weights=df['weights']).fit()
    #non linear with including log, power, exponential, chapman richards
    def power(x, a,b):
        return a * x**b
    powerModel = Model(power)
    pParams = powerModel.make_params(a=0.5, b=1)
    pParams['a'].set(min=0)
    pParams['b'].set(min=0)
    pResult = powerModel.fit(df[f'{yName}'], pParams, x =df[f'{xName}'], weights=df['weights'])
    def CR(x, a, b, c):
        return a * (1 - np.exp(-b * x))**c
    CRModel = Model(CR)
    CRParams = CRModel.make_params(a=(df[f'{yName}'].max()), b=0.03, c=2)
    CRParams['a'].set(min=0)
    CRParams['b'].set(min=0)
    CRParams['c'].set(min=0)
    CRResult = CRModel.fit(df[f'{yName}'].values, CRParams, x=df[f'{xName}'].values, nan_policy='omit', weights=df['weights'])
    def log(x, a, b):
        return a * np.log(x) + b
    logModel = Model(log)
    lParams = logModel.make_params(a=0.5, b=1)
    lResult = logModel.fit(df[f'{yName}'], lParams, x=df[f'{xName}'], nan_policy='omit', weights=df['weights'])
    
    # QUICK LOOK TO COMPARE MODEL OUTCOMES
    # Mean Percentage Error
    def mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred):
        y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
        nonzero_mask = y_true != 0
        if not np.any(nonzero_mask):
        # All y_true are zero, can't compute MPE
            return np.nan
        mpe = np.mean((y_true[nonzero_mask] - y_pred[nonzero_mask]) / y_true[nonzero_mask]) * 100
        return mpe
    def evaluate_model(name, y_true, y_pred, formula):
        return {
        'Model': name,
        'Formula': formula,
        'R²': r2_score(y_true, y_pred),
        'RMSE': np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)),
        'MPE': mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred)
    }
    results_list = []
    y_pred_linear = results.predict(df)
    formula_linear = f"{yName} = {results.params['Intercept']:.3f} + {results.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Linear', df[yName], y_pred_linear, formula_linear))
    y_pred_poly2 = poly2.predict(df)
    formula_poly2 = (f"{yName} = {poly2.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}²")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (2nd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly2, formula_poly2))
    y_pred_poly3 = poly3.predict(df)
    formula_poly3 = (f"{yName} = {poly3.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}² + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)']:.3f} * {xName}³")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (3rd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly3, formula_poly3))
    y_pred_log = lResult.eval(x=df[xName])
    aL = lResult.params['a'].value
    bL = lResult.params['b'].value
    formula_log = f"{yName} = {aL:.3f} * ln({xName}) + {bL:.3f}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Logarithmic', df[yName], y_pred_log, formula_log))
    y_pred_power = pResult.eval(x=df[xName])
    aP = pResult.params['a'].value
    bP = pResult.params['b'].value
    formula_power = f"{yName} = {aP:.14f} * {xName} ^ {bP:.3f}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Power', df[yName], y_pred_power, formula_power))
    y_pred_CR = CRResult.eval(x=df[xName])
    aCR = CRResult.params['a'].value
    bCR = CRResult.params['b'].value
    cCR = CRResult.params['c'].value
    formula_CR = f"{yName} = {aCR:.3f} * (1 - exp(-{bCR:.3f} * {xName})) ^ {cCR:.3f}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Chapman-Richards', df[yName], y_pred_CR, formula_CR))
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(results_list)
    metrics_df = metrics_df.sort_values(by='R²', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
    

    #GRAPH RESULTS
    # Create x values
    x_vals = np.linspace(1.3 * df[xName].min(), 1.3 * df[xName].max(), 200)
    # Scatter plots of original data
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 6))
    axs[0].scatter(df[xName], df[yName], label='Inventory Data', color='blue', alpha=0.6, s=20)
    axs[1].scatter(df[xName], df[yName], label='Inventory Data', color='blue', alpha=0.6, s=15)
    # Linear
    y_vals_linear = results.params['Intercept'] + results.params[xName] * x_vals
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_linear, label='Linear', color='blue', linestyle='-')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_linear, label='Linear', color='blue', linestyle='-')
    # Polynomial 2nd degree
    y_vals_poly2 = (poly2.params['Intercept'] 
                + poly2.params[xName] * x_vals 
                + poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2)
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly2, label='Polynomial (2nd)', color='green', linestyle='--')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly2, label='Polynomial (2nd)', color='green', linestyle='--')
    # Polynomial 3rd degree
    y_vals_poly3 = (
    poly3.params['Intercept'] 
    + poly3.params[xName] * x_vals 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)'] * x_vals**3
    )
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly3, label='Polynomial (3rd)', color='darkgreen', linestyle=':')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly3, label='Polynomial (3rd)', color='darkgreen', linestyle=':')
    # Power
    aP = pResult.params['a'].value
    bP = pResult.params['b'].value
    y_vals_power = aP * x_vals**bP
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_power, label='Power', color='purple', linestyle='-.', linewidth = 2)
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_power, label='Power', color='purple', linestyle='-.', linewidth = 2)
    # Logarithmic (only valid for x_vals > 0)
    x_vals_log = x_vals[x_vals > 0]
    y_vals_log = lResult.params['a'].value * np.log(x_vals_log) + lResult.params['b'].value
    axs[0].plot(x_vals_log, y_vals_log, label='Logarithmic', color='orange', linestyle='--')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals_log, y_vals_log, label='Logarithmic', color='orange', linestyle='--')
    # Chapman-Richards
    aCR = CRResult.params['a'].value
    bCR = CRResult.params['b'].value
    cCR = CRResult.params['c'].value
    y_vals_CR = aCR * (1 - np.exp(-bCR * x_vals))**cCR
    axs[0].plot(x_vals, y_vals_CR, label='Chapman-Richards', color='brown', linestyle='-.')
    axs[1].plot(x_vals, y_vals_CR, label='Chapman-Richards', color='brown', linestyle='-.')
    # Final plot formatting
    axs[0].set_ylim(-5, 45)
    axs[0].set_xlim(0,(1.2*df[xName].max()))
    axs[1].set_ylim(-.01, .4)
    axs[1].set_xlim(0,50)
    for ax in axs.flat:
        ax.set(xlabel='Age', ylabel='Biomass per Tree (tC)')
    plt.suptitle('Predicting Biomass per Tree Given Inventory Data')

    return metrics_df

Model Selection
RRG has chosen the Chapman-Richard's sigmoid curve for lifecycle modeling. RRG understands model tests indicate low model performance. Because RRG heavily weighed the lower portion of the dataset, all statistical tests are expected to be negatively impacted. Moving into the future, RRG and PEF will collect additional inventory data to strengthen model results.

def biomass_t(Age):
    biomass =  0.105 * (1 - np.exp(-0.091 * Age)) ** 0.831
    return(biomass)

Quantifying Uncertainty with Quartile-Based Performance Scenarios¶

RRG understands the complexity of forest restoration and the need for a sliding scale of performance biomass outcomes. RRG trained the models with the understanding that project activities cannot outpreform existing old-growth forests in biomass growth. In conjunction, RRG needs to estimate worse case scenarios where poor site conditions (competing vegetation, dry) or catastrophic risk events influence growth. So, RRG has prepared quartile based scaling scenarios for ex-ante predictions of carbon removals:

  • Low Performing Models (25%)
  • Mid Performing Models (50-75%)
  • High Performing Models (100%)

Leakage¶

The Lushoto district has minimal available data regarding historical grower records and illegal logging rates. RRG can see from remote sensing that farms throughout the project zone are quite small and are believed to be subsistence farms.
Moving into the future, RRG and FOU will complete the FPIC process and hold local farmer interviews to determine foregone production within the project area. It is not anticipated that project activities will not displace any farms within the project area. FOU aims to mitigate leakage into the surrounding region by employing these farmers and providing them with an alternate, sustainable livelihood.
Until the FPIC process occurs, RRG has decided to implement the default leakage deductions set out in the Verra Standard, v4.7. These deductions are taken from the gross Co2e removals and are 15% from activity shifting leakage and 10% from market shifting leakage.
RRG will ultimately use the VM0054 ARR Leakage module to calculate leakage. This module first estimates leakage by calculating production (based on grower records), an anticipated amount of new land brought into production and the determination of the change in carbon stock due to this land change. Cumulatively, the following equation describes how RRG will quantify leakage.

For ex-ante estimations, leakage must be quantified in tCo2. To do this with the default 25% rate, RRG takes 25% of total Co2e removals from each performance scenario.

In [87]:
def leak(mass):
    metric = mass * 0.25
    return(metric)

Remote Sensing Performance Benchmark¶

Modeling of SI at Biomass¶

RRG has compared a range of stocking indices (SI) to monitor biomass accumulation. Below RRG compares a simple and complex biomass model.

Simple Regression¶

SAR backscatter images are representations of the microwave portion of the electromagnetic spectrum. SAR data is commonly used for detecting forest changes and is less suceptible to seasonal variations. The following equation sums the model: $$ \text{Biomass} = f(\text{SAR HV}) $$ $$ \text{where Biomass = WCMC Aboveground and Belowground Biomass} $$

Model Design
It's important to note that HV (db) index values are negative. Because of this, not all parametric models will work , only linear and polynomial equations will work. Due to this, RRG additionally uses Gradient Boosted ML models.

In [102]:
def SI_model(data):
    df = data.copy()
    x = df.iloc[:, 0]
    y = df.iloc[:, 1]
    xName = df.columns[0]
    yName = df.columns[1]
    # PARAMETRIC MODELING
    #linear modeling/polynomial 
    results = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName}', data=df).fit()
    poly2 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2)', data=df).fit()
    poly3 = smf.wls(f'{yName} ~ {xName} + I({xName}**2) + I({xName}**3)', data=df).fit()
    # QUICK LOOK TO COMPARE MODEL OUTCOMES
    # Mean Percentage Error
    def mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred):
        y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
        nonzero_mask = y_true != 0
        if not np.any(nonzero_mask):
        # All y_true are zero, can't compute MPE
            return np.nan
        mpe = np.mean((y_true[nonzero_mask] - y_pred[nonzero_mask]) / y_true[nonzero_mask]) * 100
        return mpe
    def evaluate_model(name, y_true, y_pred, formula):
        return {
        'Model': name,
        'Formula': formula,
        'R²': r2_score(y_true, y_pred),
        'RMSE': np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)),
        'MPE': mean_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred)
    }
    results_list = []
    y_pred_linear = results.predict(df)
    formula_linear = f"{yName} = {results.params['Intercept']:.3f} + {results.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName}"
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Linear', df[yName], y_pred_linear, formula_linear))
    y_pred_poly2 = poly2.predict(df)
    formula_poly2 = (f"{yName} = {poly2.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}²")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (2nd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly2, formula_poly2))
    y_pred_poly3 = poly3.predict(df)
    formula_poly3 = (f"{yName} = {poly3.params['Intercept']:.3f} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[xName]:.3f} * {xName} + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)']:.3f} * {xName}² + "
                 f"{poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)']:.3f} * {xName}³")
    results_list.append(evaluate_model('Polynomial (3rd)', df[yName], y_pred_poly3, formula_poly3))
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(results_list)
    metrics_df = metrics_df.sort_values(by='R²', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
    #GRAPH RESULTS
    # Create x values
    x_vals = np.linspace(1.3 * df[xName].min(), 1.3 * df[xName].max(), 200)
    # Scatter plots of original data
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.scatter(df[xName], df[yName], label='GEE Data', color='lightblue', alpha=0.6, s=20)
    # Linear
    y_vals_linear = results.params['Intercept'] + results.params[xName] * x_vals
    plt.plot(x_vals, y_vals_linear, label='Linear', color='blue', linestyle='-')
    # Polynomial 2nd degree
    y_vals_poly2 = (poly2.params['Intercept'] 
                + poly2.params[xName] * x_vals 
                + poly2.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2)
    plt.plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly2, label='Polynomial (2nd)', color='green', linestyle='--')
    # Polynomial 3rd degree
    y_vals_poly3 = (
    poly3.params['Intercept'] 
    + poly3.params[xName] * x_vals 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 2)'] * x_vals**2 
    + poly3.params[f'I({xName} ** 3)'] * x_vals**3
    )
    plt.plot(x_vals, y_vals_poly3, label='Polynomial (3rd)', color='darkgreen', linestyle=':')
    # Final plot formatting
    plt.ylim(-1, (1.2*df[yName].max()))
    plt.xlim((1.2* df[xName].min()), (1.2*df[xName].max()))
    plt.xlabel('HV Index Value (dB)')
    plt.ylabel('Biomass per ha (tC)')
    plt.title('Predicting Biomass per Hectare Given SAR HV Data')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    return metrics_df

def applyQualityMask(image):
    # Assuming 'MSK' is the data quality mask band
    msk = image.select('qa')
    # Mask out pixels with value 50 (commonly water/invalid in ALOS PALSAR)
    mask = msk.neq(50)
    masked_image = image.updateMask(mask)
    return masked_image
def convertToGammaNaught(image):
    # Convert DN to gamma naught (γ₀) in decibels
    gamma_naught = image.pow(2).log10().multiply(10).subtract(83)
    return gamma_naught

Model Selection
When comparing model results and curve shapes, RRG chose the 2nd Polynomial equation for export due to it's high end (100-140ha) biomass estimates. Moving into the future, RRG will add additional biomass datasets to refine these models.

def biomass_HV(HV):
    biomass = 141.26 + 8.36 * HV + 0.1 * HV**2 
    return(biomass)

Complex Model¶

In addition to SAR HV, RRG will use a range of available geospatial data to monitor biomass accumulation. The following equation describes the model: $$ \text{Biomass} = f(\text{SAR HV, NDVI, Slope}) $$ $$ \text{where Biomass = WCMC Aboveground and Belowground Biomass} $$

Model Design
RRG has chosen to compare multiple linear regression and support vector regression models.

In [143]:
def mlr(data):
    df = data.copy()
    features = ['NDVI', 'HV']
    x = df[features]
    y = df.iloc[:,0]
    # Split dataset (80% train, 20% test)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
    # Scale features
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
    # Initialize and train model
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    # Predict on test data
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    reg_model_diff = pd.DataFrame({'Actual value': y_test, 'Predicted value': y_pred}) 
    # Calculate residuals
    residuals = y_test - y_pred
    # Evaluation
    print("Intercept:", model.intercept_)
    print("Coefficients:", list(zip(x.columns, model.coef_)))
    print("R² on test set:", r2_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("MSE on test set:", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    print("RMSE on test set:", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))
    # graph results
    # Create meshgrid for surface
    x1_range = np.linspace(X_train_scaled[:, 0].min(), X_train_scaled[:, 0].max(), 50)
    x2_range = np.linspace(X_train_scaled[:, 1].min(), X_train_scaled[:, 1].max(), 50)
    X1_mesh, X2_mesh = np.meshgrid(x1_range, x2_range)
    grid_points = np.c_[X1_mesh.ravel(), X2_mesh.ravel()]
    y_pred_mesh = model.predict(grid_points).reshape(X1_mesh.shape)
    # Inverse transform for better axis labels
    grid_points_unscaled = scaler.inverse_transform(grid_points)
    X1_unscaled = grid_points_unscaled[:, 0].reshape(X1_mesh.shape)
    X2_unscaled = grid_points_unscaled[:, 1].reshape(X2_mesh.shape)
    X_train_inv = scaler.inverse_transform(X_train_scaled)
    # Plot with Plotly
    fig = go.Figure()
    # Add training data points
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter3d(
        x=X_train_inv[:, 0], y=X_train_inv[:, 1], z=y_train,
        mode='markers',
        marker=dict(size=5, color='blue', opacity=0.7),
        name='Train Data'
    ))
    # Add prediction surface
    fig.add_trace(go.Surface(
        x=X1_unscaled,
        y=X2_unscaled,
        z=y_pred_mesh,
        colorscale='Viridis',
        opacity=0.6,
        name='Regression Plane'
    ))
    fig.update_layout(
        scene=dict(
            xaxis_title=features[0],
            yaxis_title=features[1],
            zaxis_title='Biomass'
        ),
        title="3D Linear Regression with Prediction Surface",
        width=800,
        height=500
    )
    fig.show()

def svr(data):
    df = data.copy()
    features = ['NDVI', 'HV']
    x = df[features]
    y = df.iloc[:,0]
    # Split dataset (80% train, 20% test)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
    # Scale features
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
    # Initialize and train model
    model = SVR(kernel='rbf', C=10, epsilon=.1, gamma=.5)
    model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
    # Predict on test data
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    print("R² on test set:", r2_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("MSE on test set:", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    print("RMSE on test set:", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))
    # graph results
    # Create meshgrid for surface
    x1_range = np.linspace(X_train_scaled[:, 0].min(), X_train_scaled[:, 0].max(), 50)
    x2_range = np.linspace(X_train_scaled[:, 1].min(), X_train_scaled[:, 1].max(), 50)
    X1_mesh, X2_mesh = np.meshgrid(x1_range, x2_range)
    grid_points = np.c_[X1_mesh.ravel(), X2_mesh.ravel()]
    y_pred_mesh = model.predict(grid_points).reshape(X1_mesh.shape)
    # Inverse transform for better axis labels
    grid_points_unscaled = scaler.inverse_transform(grid_points)
    X1_unscaled = grid_points_unscaled[:, 0].reshape(X1_mesh.shape)
    X2_unscaled = grid_points_unscaled[:, 1].reshape(X2_mesh.shape)
    X_train_inv = scaler.inverse_transform(X_train_scaled)
    # Plot with Plotly
    fig = go.Figure()
    # Add training data points
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter3d(
        x=X_train_inv[:, 0], y=X_train_inv[:, 1], z=y_train,
        mode='markers',
        marker=dict(size=5, color='blue', opacity=0.7),
        name='Train Data'
    ))
    # Add prediction surface
    fig.add_trace(go.Surface(
        x=X1_unscaled,
        y=X2_unscaled,
        z=y_pred_mesh,
        colorscale='Viridis',
        opacity=0.6,
        name='Regression Plane'
    ))
    fig.update_layout(
        scene=dict(
            xaxis_title=features[0],
            yaxis_title=features[1],
            zaxis_title='Biomass'
        ),

def applyQualityMask(image):
    # Assuming 'MSK' is the data quality mask band
    msk = image.select('qa')
    # Mask out pixels with value 50 (commonly water/invalid in ALOS PALSAR)
    mask = msk.neq(50)
    masked_image = image.updateMask(mask)
    return masked_image
def convertToGammaNaught(image):
    # Convert DN to gamma naught (γ₀) in decibels
    gamma_naught = image.pow(2).log10().multiply(10).subtract(83)
    return gamma_naught
collection = (
    palsar
    .map(convertToGammaNaught)  # Convert DN to gamma naught
    .map(applyQualityMask)
)
palsarImage = collection.median().clip(usamGeom)
hvImage = palsarImage.select('HV') 
hhImage = palsarImage.select('HH')

    .filterDate(f'{year}-12-01', f'{year + 1}-02-01').filterBounds(projectsites)
print(landsat.size().getInfo())
def scale_sr(img):
    red = img.select('SR_B3').multiply(0.0000275).add(-0.2).rename('RED')
    nir = img.select('SR_B4').multiply(0.0000275).add(-0.2).rename('NIR')
    return img.addBands([red, nir], overwrite=True)
def mask_l7_sr(image):
    qa = image.select('QA_PIXEL')
    mask = qa.bitwiseAnd(1 << 0).eq(0)   \
           .And(qa.bitwiseAnd(1 << 3).eq(0))  \
           .And(qa.bitwiseAnd(1 << 5).eq(0))    
    return image.updateMask(mask) 
# Apply to each image
scaled_collection = landsat.map(scale_sr).map(mask_l7_sr)
# Median composite
image = scaled_collection.median().clip(usamGeom)
# Calculate NDVI
ndvi = image.normalizedDifference(['NIR', 'RED']).rename('NDVI')

Baseline Biomass¶

RRG will utilize time series analysis to determine the baseline conditions of the project sites at three distinct time periods from t=-8, t=-3, and t=0. This corresponds to 2015, 2020 and 2023.

Using the Simple Model (x=SAR HV, y=UN Biomass 2010)¶

RRG utilized the Jaxa yearly mosaic going back to 2010 for the training models. However, this dataset does not provide data beyond 2020. Despite this, Jaxa provides multiple datasets with more up to date data. RRG will utilize this dataset for baseline biomass analysis.

Visualize Change from Pre to Post Project Activities¶

RRG has slowly rolled out monitoring programs including seedling verification and remote sensing. With this data, it's evident many of the sites should not have significant biomass change. Many of the seedlings are 0.5-1 m tall. In addition, at many sites FOU needed to cut rows through the dense bushlands which may result in decreases in biomass. It is expected these biomass changes will increase dramatically in the next 1-3 years.

ANOVA Testing¶

Throughout the project lifetime, RRG will utilize ANOVA, or Analysis of Variance, to statistically test to determine if there are significant differences between the mean HV values pre to post planting. It is assumed that as seedlings grow, their HV values increase.

In [76]:
# Find mean HV values for each year
mean_ad = anova_df.groupby('SiteName')[['HH_2023', 'HH_2025']].median().reset_index()
comp_anova = mean_ad
comp_anova.columns.values[0]='Site'
comp_anova.columns.values[1]='Mean HV 2023'
comp_anova.columns.values[2]='Mean HV 2025'
df_long = pd.melt(anova_df, id_vars='SiteName', value_vars=['HH_2023', 'HH_2025'],
                  var_name='Year', value_name='HH_Value')
def anova_two_years(site_df):
    group1 = site_df['HH_2023']
    group2 = site_df['HH_2025']
    f_stat, p_val = f_oneway(group1, group2)
    return pd.Series({'F_stat': f_stat, 'p_value': p_val})

anova_result = anova_df.groupby('SiteName').apply(anova_two_years).reset_index()
anova_result.columns.values[0]='Site'
anova_merge = pd.merge(anova_result, comp_anova, on='Site')
anova_merge = anova_merge.iloc[:,[0,3,4,1,2]]
# Set pandas options for nicer table display in console/notebook

pd.set_option('display.max_columns', None)
pd.set_option('display.precision', 2)
print(anova_merge)

Interpreting Results¶

With this ANOVA test, RRG can statistically validate the difference in HV values from 2023 to 2025. RRG understands this test only included two years. In the near future, RRG will expand this analysis to include a broad range of years.

Model Performance Discussion¶

RRG can estimate historical biomass and future biomass of the project area utilizing SI and machine learning. RRG understands that model performance varies between datasets and that improvements can be made. Moving into the future, RRG will include model updates for the following categories:

  • Field Inventory Models
    • Model Results
      • R2 values near 0 due to LiDAR training weights
      • High RMSE due to LiDAR training weights
      • Negative MPE indicating underfitting due to LiDAR training weights
    • Model Upgrades
      • Quartile Regression to compare to parametric regression with training weights
      • Add additional datapoints with FOU field data
  • SI/Biomass Models
    • Simple Model Results
      • R2 values near 0.55
      • High RMSE due to dataset noise
      • Negative MPE indicating underfitting
    • Complex Model Results
      • R2 values near 0.4
      • High RMSE due to dataset noise
      • Negative MPE indicating underfitting
    • Model Upgrades
      • Additional SI predictors including LiDAR Canopy Height
      • Additional biomass data including NASA 2010 dataset, GEDI datasets from 2019-2024
      • More complex models including XGB Boost, Artifical Neural Network (ANN)

RRG understands the importance of accurate remote sensing and field monitoring systems to quantify biomass changes throughout the project lifetime. This document will serve as a living library and will be updated as RRG makes upgrades.
